Three efficiencies

1st law: actual, thermal efficiency;
\(\eta_1 =\frac{W_{net}}{Q_{in}}=\frac{Q_{high}-Q_{low}}{Q_{high}}=1-\frac{Q_{low}}{Q_{high}}\)
Carnot: maximum possible efficiency;
\(\eta_c =\frac{W_{net}}{Q_{high}}=\frac{T_{high}-T_{low}}{T_{high}}=1-\frac{T_{low}}{T_{high}}\) (Kelvin)

2nd law: comparing 1st and Carnot;
\(\eta_2 =\frac{\eta_1}{\eta_c}\)


Read more: Sadi Carnot

Learning Objectives

Develop comprehensive understanding of energy systems, i.e. the interaction of technological, social, economic, and regulatory forces that shaping energy production, conversion, and consumption;
Gain an understanding of main data sources and key methods used to analyze energy systems and their strengths and weaknesses;
Get introduced to major analytical concepts and modeling tools used in energy systems and policy analysis;
Develop basic analytical skills to translate energy systems analysis into effective policy discussion and debate.

Learning Objectives

Develop comprehensive understanding the scientific foundation, economic rational, systems complexity, and policy implications of climate change, energy transtion, and human society;
Gain a system understanding of the energy root of climate challenges, and the technology, economic, societal, behavral transformation needed to enable an energy transition;
Get introduced to major analytical concepts and case studies in energy and climate systems and policy analysis;
Develop basic analytical skills to understand and contribute effective policy discussion and debate.
